elgrade]]\n| [[Beogradska Arena|Belgrade Arena]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]]\n|-\n| {{RUS}}\n| [[Moscow]]\n| [[Olympic Stadium (Moscow arena)|Olympic Stadium]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]]\n|-\n| {{AZE}}\n| [[Baku]]\n| [[Baku Crystal Hall]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]]\n|-\n| {{POR}}\n| [[Lisbon]]\n| [[Altice Arena]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Anniversary events==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Anniversary\n!Country\n!City\n!Venue\n!Event\n!Year\n|-\n| 25th\n| {{NOR}}\n| [[Mysen]]\n| [[Momarken]]\n| [[Songs of Europe (1981 concert)|Songs of Europe]]\n| 1981\n|-\n| 50th\n| {{DEN}}\n| [[Copenhagen]]\n| [[Forum Copenhagen]]\n| [[Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n| 2005\n|-\n| 60th\n| {{GBR}}\n| [[London]]\n| [[Eventim Apollo]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits]]\n| 2015\n|-\n|}\nThe following are alternate events, not made specifically for an anniversary, but for other reasons\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Anniversary\n!Country\n!City\n!Venue\n!Event\n!Year\n!Replacing\n!Reason\n|-\n|65th\n|[[File:Flag_of_the_Netherlands.svg|link=Netherlands|alt=Netherlands|23x23px]] [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |TBC\n|[[Eurovision: Europe Shine a Light|Eurovision: Europe Shine A Light]]\n|2020\n|[[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]]\n|[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 outbreak]]\n|}\n<br />\n==Host City Insignia==\n[[File:ESC Host City Insignia.jpg|thumb|175px|right|The Host City Insignia on display inside the [[Rathaus,_Vienna|Rathaus]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], in May 2015. ]]\n'''Host City Insignia''' is a rotating trophy awarded to cities hosting the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. The symbol is a large key ring to which the Eurovision Song Contest Host Cities can attach their city key or other symbol representing the city. The Host City Insignia Exchange usually takes place in conjunction with the Semi-Final Allocation Draw. The insignia is traditionally put on display in a public place, such as the City Hall or another venue of local significance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/about/in-depth/host-city-insignia-exchange/|title=Host City Insignia Exchange|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> Additionally, there is a fob with a picture of the [[Helsinki Senate Square]] attached to the key ring.\n\nThe idea of the rotating trophy was proposed jointly by the City of [[Helsinki]], the Finnish Broadcasting Company [[YLE]] and [[EBU]] in connection with the 2007 Eurovision Song Contest. Hand-engraved on the ring are the following texts: \"Eurovision Song Contest Host City\", all Host Cities up until the year 2006 and a stamp: Helsinki 2007 with the initials of the prize designers. The concept and fob were designed by the ANTEEKSI Team and the ring by jewellery designer Taru Tonder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Badzic|first1=Milenko|title=Host City Insignia Exchange & Semi-Final Allocation Draw|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/press/photo-downloads?gal=123813&type=Press|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=26 March 2017|date=26 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327081350/http://www.eurovision.tv/page/press/photo-downloads?gal=123813&type=Press|archivedate=27 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212182218/http://www.hel.fi/wps/portal/Hallintokeskus_en/Artikkeli?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=%2FHalke%2Fen%2FNews%20and%20Press%20releases%2FUutiset|title=Open Doors Weekend fills Helsinki with design|website=City of Helsinki news|date=31 January 2012|language=Finnish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611105333/http://www.hel.fi/wps/portal/Hallintokeskus/Artikkeli?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=%2FHalke%2Ffi%2Fuutiset%2Bja%2Btiedotteet%2Fhallintokeskuksen%2Btiedotteet%2Fhelsinki%2Baloittaa%2Buuden%2Beurovision%2Blaulukilpailun%2Bperinteen|trans-title=Helsinki begins the tradition of the new Eurovision Song Contest|title=Helsinki aloittaa uuden Eurovision laulukilpailun perinteen|language=Finnish|date=15 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Semi-final allotment drawing venue==\nSince the introduction in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]] of the two semi-finals system, a drawing has been held to determine in which semi-final a country would participate, as well as in which semi-final a country would vote in. Each year, either five or six countries are exempt from the drawing for competing in the semi-finals: the big-five (France, Germany, Italy, Spain, and UK), and the host country, if the host is not one of the big five. In [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015|2015]] the number of countries exempt was seven, as Australia joined the other six countries exempt because the country was considered a special guest contestant.\n\nRegardless if a country is exempt from competing in the semi-finals, all participating countries are allotted a semi-final in which to vote. \n \n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Days prior<br>to first<br>semi-final\n! Venue\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008}}\n| align=\"right\" | 142\n| [[Stari dvor|Old Palace]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009}}\n| align=\"right\" | 102\n| Marriott Royal Aurora Hotel, Moscow\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010}}\n| align=\"right\" | 107\n| ''Euroclub'' at {{ill|Smuget|no}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2011}}\n| align=\"right\" | 113\n| Esprit Arena\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012}}\n| align=\"right\" | 118\n| [[Buta Palace]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013}}\n| align=\"right\" | 117\n| {{ill|Malm\u00f6 City Hall|sv|Malm\u00f6 r\u00e5dhus}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014}}\n| align=\"right\" | 106\n| [[Copenhagen City Hall]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2015}}\n| align=\"right\" | 113\n| [[Vienna City Hall|Vienna Rathaus]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2016}}\n| align=\"right\" | 106\n| [[Stockholm City Hall]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2017}}\n| align