ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/kan-eurovision-2019-update-press-conference|title=Lots of Eurovision 2019 news during Host Broadcaster press conference|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=15 April 2019|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=#87A96B\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020]]\n| [[Rotterdam Cruise Terminal]]\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2020/03/11/eurovision20-opening-ceremony-to-be-held-at-cruise-terminal/|title=Eurovision'20: Opening Ceremony To Be Held at Cruise Terminal|date=2020-03-11|website=Eurovoix|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of host cities of the ABU Song Festivals]]\n* [[List of host cities of the Junior Eurovision Song Contest]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|close}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Venues of the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n* [http://www.esctoday.com/multimedia/gallery/450 The picture of the insignia on the page of the Eurovision Song Contest Moscow 2009]\n* [http://www.hs.fi/english/picture/1135230307942 A photo on the web pages of the biggest newspaper Helsingin Sanomat with description \"Helsinki Mayor Jussi Pajunen (left) and cultural director Pekka Timonen were in Belgrade on Friday to hand over the Helsinki Insignia to the city that will host next year's Eurovision Song Contest.\"] ([[Helsingin Sanomat]])\n\n{{eurovision years}}\n\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest related lists|Host cities, list of]]\n[[Category:Music-related lists|Host cities of the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n[[Category:Lists of host cities|Eurovision Song Contest]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=August 2011}}\n[[File:Eurovision all cities.svg|thumb|400px|Countries which have hosted the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]\n{{efn|name=yug|In 1990 the former country of Yugoslavia hosted the contest in the [[Zagreb|City of Zagreb]], which is in present day Croatia. Croatia, as an independent country, has not yet hosted the contest. The map shows the six countries that formerly made up the country of Yugoslavia, and cannot also simultaneously show Yugoslavia}}\n{{Columns\n|col1={{legend|#4d9221|A single hosting}}\n|col2={{legend|#c51b7d|Multiple hostings}}\n}}]]\nThis page is a '''list of cities and venues that have hosted the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]''', one or more times. Future venues are shown in ''italics''. Since [[Eurovision Song Contest 1958|1958]], the host city has customarily been in the country that won the contest the previous year. [[Eurovision Song Contest#Host country|There have been exceptions]], however, when certain issues (usually financial) prevented the winner from hosting the following year's contest. The exceptions occurred in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1960|1960]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1963|1963]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1972|1972]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1974|1974]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]].<ref>[http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history#By_year The history of the Eurovision Song Contest - By year] Official Eurovision Website History. Accessed May 2012</ref> In all but one of those exceptions, the UK hosted the Eurovision. The custom of having the winning country host the Eurovision the following year has now been observed for 39 consecutive years. <!-- 40 years once The Netherlands hosts in 2020 -->\n\nHaving hosted the contest six times, [[Dublin]] holds the record for having hosted the contest most often. It is followed by [[London]] and [[Luxembourg_(city)|Luxembourg]] (each hosted 4 contests), then [[Copenhagen]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dr.dk/event/melodigrandprix/koebenhavn-bliver-vaert-internationalt-melodi-grand-prix|title=K\u00f8benhavn bliver v\u00e6rt for internationalt Melodi Grand Prix|work=DR|access-date=2017-05-08|language=da}}</ref> and [[Stockholm]] (each hosted 3 contests).\n\n[[Image:BBC Television Centre.JPG|thumb|150px|[[BBC Television Centre]] in [[London]] hosted the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1963|1963 Contest]].]]\n[[Image:Scandinavium entre 2005.jpg|thumb|150px|The [[Scandinavium]] in [[Gothenburg]]: venue for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1985|1985 Contest]].]]\n[[Image:Cinecitta studios rome italy entrance.jpg|thumb|150px|The film studios at [[Cinecitt\u00e0]] in [[Rome]] played host to the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1991|1991 Contest]].]]\n[[Image:Oslo Spektrum.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Oslo Spektrum]] was the venue for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996 Contest]].]]\n[[Image:Athens Olympic Indoor Hall - exterior.jpg|thumb|150px|The [[O.A.C.A. Olympic Indoor Hall|Athens Olympic Indoor Hall]] in [[Athens]] hosted the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2006|2006 Contest]].]]\n[[Image:Belgrade Arena north.jpg|thumb|150px|The [[Belgrade Arena]] hosted the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008 Contest]].]]\n[[Image:Wiener Stadthalle Aussen 2008.jpg|thumb|150px|The [[Wiener Stadthalle]] hosted the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015|2015 Contest]].]]\n[[Image:Rotterdam Ahoy 2016.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Rotterdam Ahoy]] was the planned host of the now cancelled [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020 Contest]].]]\n\n== Eurovision Song Contest ==\n;Table key\n{{legend|#F88379|Former countries that have been dissolved.}}\n{{legend|#87A96B|Cancelled edition.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Contests\n!Country\n!City\n!Venue\n!Years\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"| 8\n|rowspan=\"8\"| {{GBR}}\n|rowspan=\"4\"| [[London]]\n| [[Royal Festival Hall]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 1960|1960]]\n|-\n| [[BBC Television Centre]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 1963|1963]]\n|-\n| [[Royal Albert Hall]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 1968|1968]]\n|-\n| [[Wembley Conference Centre]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 1977|1977]]\n|-\n| [[Edinburgh]]\n| [[Usher Hall]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 1972|1972]]\n|-\n| [[Brighton]]\n| [[Brighton Dome]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 1974|1974]]\n|-\n| [[Harrogate]]\n| [[Harrogate International Centre]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 1982|1982]]\n|-\n| [[