wheader=true|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Slovenia ([[SloTop50]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slotop50.si/Glasbene-lestvice/Tedenske-lestvice/?year=2020&week=15|title=SloTop50 \u2013 Slovenian official singles chart|publisher=slotop50.si|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 13\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|35|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|8|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ukraine|8|rowheader=true|date=2020-04-10|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of number-one singles of 2020 (Poland)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ava Max}}\n\n[[Category:2019 singles]]\n[[Category:2018 songs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Ava Max songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Poland]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Cirkut (record producer)]]\n\n{{2019-single-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 single by Ava Max}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name        = Salt\n| cover       = Ava Max Salt New Cover.jpg\n| alt         = Salt is sprinkled across a black background, forming Max's signature haircut logo. There is no text on the cover.\n| type        = single\n| artist      = [[Ava Max]]\n| album       =\n| released    = {{start date|2019|12|12|mf=y}}\n| format      =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded    = 2018\n| genre       = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[dance-pop]]<ref name=\"MTV Salt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3148895/ava-max-salt/|title=Ava Max Finally Unleashes The Fan-Favorite Anthem 'Salt'|last=Roth|first=Madeline|website=[[MTV News]]|date=December 12, 2019|access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>}}<!--Add source when listing genre-->\n| length      = {{duration|m=3}}\n| label       = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer      = {{hlist|[[Ava Max|Amanda Koci]]|[[Autumn Rowe]]|[[Cirkut (record producer)|Henry Walter]]|[[Madison Love]]|[[Coco Morier|Nicole Morier]]}}\n| producer    = [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]\n| chronology  = [[Ava Max]]\n| prev_title  = [[Tab\u00fa (song)|Tab\u00fa]]\n| prev_year   = 2019\n| next_title  = [[Alone, Pt. II]]\n| next_year   = 2019\n| misc        = {{Extra album cover\n| header = Alternate cover\n| type = single\n| cover = Ava Max Salt Original Cover.jpg\n| border = yes\n| caption = Original cover\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|2EfE0vhxt1o|\"Salt\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Salt'''\" is a song by American singer [[Ava Max]], released as a single on December 12, 2019 through [[Atlantic Records]], despite having already been released to [[YouTube]] and [[SoundCloud]] in July 2018.<ref name=\"Idolator\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7904225/ava-max-is-all-cried-out-feeling-fabulous-on-fierce-new-single-salt|title=Ava Max Is All Cried Out & Feeling Fabulous On Fierce New Single Salt|last=Nied|first=Mike|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|date=December 12, 2019|access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> The song has also been regarded as a \"fan favorite\".<ref name=\"MTV Salt\"/><ref name=\"Idolator\"/><ref name=\"BillboardRelease\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8546157/ava-max-salt-listen|title=Ava Max Finally Drops Fan Favorite Song 'Salt'|last=Aniftos|first=Rania|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=December 12, 2019|access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background and composition==\n\"Salt\" was initially released on several streaming platforms in July 2018 as a promotional single, which included [[YouTube]] and [[SoundCloud]].<ref name=\"MTV Salt\"/> On December 5, 2019, Max revealed the song's release date on social media,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AvaMax/status/1202724362417139713|title=Your wish is my command \u2763\ufe0f\ud83d\ude80|via=[[Twitter]]|date=December 5, 2019|access-date=December 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206064554/https://twitter.com/AvaMax/status/1202724362417139713|archive-date=December 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which was subsequently released on all streaming platforms on December 12, 2019.<ref name=\"BillboardRelease\"/>\n\nIt is described as a song filled with \"pumping disco beats from the seventies and eighties\", blended with Max's \"vocal inflexions\".<ref name=\"MusicTalkers\">{{cite web|url=https://musictalkers.com/latest-news/6232-ava-max-gets-down-to-disco-in-%E2%80%98salt%E2%80%99|title=Ava Max Gets Down To Disco In 'Salt'|last=Das|first=Shaoni|website=Music Talkers|date=December 19, 2019|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> A violin is heard in the introduction, while [[Wonder Woman]] and [[Marilyn Monroe]] are lyrically mentioned throughout the song.<ref name=\"MusicTalkers\"/> It is based on [[Time signature|{{Time signature|4|4}} common time]], the tempo is 128 [[Tempo|BPM]] and is played in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[D-sharp minor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tunebat.com/Info/Salt-Ava-Max/7vgv8KZBSo0TPzyIWG9yzV|title=Key & BPM for Salt by Ava Max - Tunebat|publisher=Tunebat|access-date=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nRania Aniftos of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' described the song as an \"upbeat, sassy track about having fun after a sad spell\",<ref name=\"BillboardRelease\"/> while Madeline Roth of [[MTV News]] felt that it was \"[[dance-pop]] blissfulness\".<ref name=\"MTV Salt\"/> Shaoni Das of ''Music Talkers'' stated that the song is an \"exhilarating dance number, awash in pools of glitter, glamour, and confidence\".<ref name=\"MusicTalkers\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''Digital download'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/salt-single/1490153026|title=Salt \u2013 Single|via=[[Apple Music]]|access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>\n#\"Salt\" \u2013 3:00\n\n*'''Digital download \u2013 acoustic'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/salt-acoustic-single/1506185126|title=Salt (Acoustic) \u2013 Single|via=[[Apple Music]]|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n#\"Salt (Acoustic)\" \u2013 3:10\n\n*'''Digital download \u2013 remixes'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/salt-the-remixes-single/1508016378|title=Salt (The Remixes) \u2013 Single|via=[[Apple Music]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n#\"Salt ([[Syn Cole]] Remix)\" \u2013 3:11\n#\"Salt (Toby Green Remix)\" \u2013 2:47\n\n* '''Streaming'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/6KPJTxKFCpuzrwyJGcURqK|title=Salt|website=[[Spotify]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226032116/https://open.spotify.com/album/6KPJTxKFCpuzrwyJGcURqK|archive-date=December 26, 2019|access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n# \"Salt\" \u2013 3:00\n# \"[[Torn (Ava Max song)|Torn]]\" \u2013 3:18\n# \"Freaking Me Out\" \u2013 3:12\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/124334771/credits|title=Salt|via=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* [[Ava Max|Amanda Ava Koci]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting\n* [[Cirkut (record producer)|Henry Walter]] \u2013 songwriting, production, mixing\n* [[Autumn Rowe]] \u2013 songwriting\n* [[Madison Love]] \u2013 songwriting\n* [[Coco Morier|Nicole Morier]] \u2013 songwriting\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|8|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|36|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|9|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|CIS|4|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|songid=98326|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Croatia ([[Croatian Radiotelevision|HRT]])<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://radio.hrt.hr/clanak/arc-100-datum-6-travnja-2020/226648/|title=Croatia ARC TOP 100|publisher=HRT|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n| 56\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=10&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 10, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| 25\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Euro Digital Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/euro-digital-song-sales|title=Euro Digital Song Sales Chart (The week of April 11, 2020)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410180005/https://www.billboard.com/charts/euro-digital-song-sales|archivedate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| 15\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|6|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=16?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 16, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| 41\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|10|songid=1928186|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarysingle|25|year=2020|week=12|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Lithuania ([[AGATA (organization)|AGATA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.agata.lt/lt/naujienos/savaites-klausomiausi-2020w16/|title=2020 16-os SAVAIT\u0116S (baland\u017eio 10-16 d.) SINGL\u0172 TOP100|publisher=[[AGATA (organization)|AGATA]]|language=Lithuanian|date=April 17, 2020|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| 39\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Norway ([[VG-lista]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://topplista.no/charts/singles/2020-w11/|title=VG-lista \u2013 Topp 20 Single uke 11, 2020|publisher=[[VG-lista]]|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 5\n|-\n{{single chart|Poland|1|chartid=3370|year=2020|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Romania ([[Airplay 100 (Romania)|Airplay 100]])<!--Please do not change this to Romanian Top 100 or Media Forest. The Airplay 100 is Romania's national singles chart from 2012 onwards. For further information, see WP:GOODCHARTS--><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kissfm.ro/podcasturi/6812|title=Airplay 100 \u2013 1 martie 2020|publisher=[[Kiss FM (Romania)|Kiss FM]]|language=Romanian|accessdate=March 2, 2020|date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n| 52\n|-\n{{single chart|Russia|3|rowheader=true|date=2020-03-13|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Slovakia|13|year=2020|week=15|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Slovakdigital|62|year=2020|week=15|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Slovenia ([[SloTop50]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slotop50.si/Glasbene-lestvice/Tedenske-lestvice/?year=2020&week=15|title=SloTop50 \u2013 Slovenian official singles chart|publisher=slotop50.si|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 13\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|35|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|8|artist=Ava Max|song=Salt|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ukraine|8|rowheader=true|date=2020-04-10|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of number-one singles of 2020 (Poland)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ava Max}}\n\n[[Category:2019 singles]]\n[[Category:2018 songs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Ava Max songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Poland]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Cirkut (record producer)]]\n\n{{2019-single-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_(Ava_Max_song)"}
{"title_page": "Hugh Thackeray Turner", "text_new": "[[File:Development Lygon Place Ebury Street - geograph.org.uk - 1194340.jpg|thumb|[[Grade II listed]] buildings in Lygon Place off [[Ebury Street]] in central London, designed by [[Eustace Balfour]] and Hugh Thackeray Turner in the [[Arts and Crafts]] style.]]\n\n'''Hugh Thackeray Turner''' (8 March 1853 \u2013 11 December 1937)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-64099|title=Turner, Hugh Thackeray (1853\u20131937), architect|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/64099|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> was an English [[Arts and Crafts]] architect and also an amateur [[china painter]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.exploringsurreyspast.org.uk/themes/people/architects/hugh_thackeray_turner/ | title=Hugh Thackeray Turner (1853 \u2013 1937)  | work=Exploring Surrey's Past | location=UK | accessdate=9 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.godalmingmuseum.org.uk/index.php?page=hugh-thackeray-turner | title=Hugh Thackeray Turner \u2013 Godalming Museum, ref: 3084 | publisher=[[Godalming Museum]] | location=UK | accessdate=9 April 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHugh Turner was born at [[Foxearth]], [[Essex]], England.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=205784 | title=Basic Biographical Details \u2013 Hugh Thackeray Turner | work=Dictionary of Scottish Architects 1840\u20131980 | location=UK | date=2008 | accessdate=9 April 2016 }}</ref> His father, Rev. John Richard Turner, was a [[Church of England]] vicar from [[Wiltshire]].\n\nTurner was apprenticed to the architect Sir [[George Gilbert Scott]] and worked under [[George Gilbert Scott, Jr.|his son]] too.\n\nTurner's buildings included Wycliffe Buildings (1894), The Court (1902), and Mead Cottage in [[Guildford]], [[Surrey]]. In 1899, Turner bought some land in [[Godalming]], Surrey, with the aim of building a house. He designed \"Westbrook\", which became his residence. He also designed the garden there. With the [[Arts and Crafts]] garden designer [[Gertrude Jekyll]], he designed the Philips Memorial Cloister on the riverside in Godalming, commemorating the bravery of Jack Philips, a hero on board the ''[[Titanic]]'' in 1912.\n\nIn 1888, Turner married the embroiderer [[Mary Elizabeth Turner|Mary Elizabeth Powell]] (1854\u20131907), the daughter of [[Thomas Wilde Powell]] from Guildford. Their daughter, Ruth, married [[George Mallory]], the climber of [[Mount Everest]] who also taught at [[Charterhouse School]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner, Hugh Thackeray}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Braintree District]]\n[[Category:Architects from Essex]]\n[[Category:Arts and Crafts architects]]\n\n\n{{England-bio-stub}}\n{{Architect-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Development Lygon Place Ebury Street - geograph.org.uk - 1194340.jpg|thumb|[[Grade II listed]] buildings in Lygon Place off [[Ebury Street]] in central London, designed by [[Eustace Balfour]] and Hugh Thackeray Turner in the [[Arts and Crafts]] style.]]\n\n'''Hugh Thackeray Turner''' (1853 \u2013 11 December 1937) was an English [[Arts and Crafts]] architect and also an amateur [[china painter]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.exploringsurreyspast.org.uk/themes/people/architects/hugh_thackeray_turner/ | title=Hugh Thackeray Turner (1853 \u2013 1937)  | work=Exploring Surrey's Past | location=UK | accessdate=9 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.godalmingmuseum.org.uk/index.php?page=hugh-thackeray-turner | title=Hugh Thackeray Turner \u2013 Godalming Museum, ref: 3084 | publisher=[[Godalming Museum]] | location=UK | accessdate=9 April 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHugh Turner was born at [[Foxearth]], [[Essex]], England.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=205784 | title=Basic Biographical Details \u2013 Hugh Thackeray Turner | work=Dictionary of Scottish Architects 1840\u20131980 | location=UK | date=2008 | accessdate=9 April 2016 }}</ref> His father, Rev. John Richard Turner, was a [[Church of England]] vicar from [[Wiltshire]].\n\nTurner was apprenticed to the architect Sir [[George Gilbert Scott]] and worked under [[George Gilbert Scott, Jr.|his son]] too.\n\nTurner's buildings included Wycliffe Buildings (1894), The Court (1902), and Mead Cottage in [[Guildford]], [[Surrey]]. In 1899, Turner bought some land in [[Godalming]], Surrey, with the aim of building a house. He designed \"Westbrook\", which became his residence. He also designed the garden there. With the [[Arts and Crafts]] garden designer [[Gertrude Jekyll]], he designed the Philips Memorial Cloister on the riverside in Godalming, commemorating the bravery of Jack Philips, a hero on board the ''[[Titanic]]'' in 1912.\n\nIn 1888, Turner married the embroiderer [[Mary Elizabeth Turner|Mary Elizabeth Powell]] (1854\u20131907), the daughter of [[Thomas Wilde Powell]] from Guildford. Their daughter, Ruth, married [[George Mallory]], the climber of [[Mount Everest]] who also taught at [[Charterhouse School]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner, Hugh Thackeray}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Braintree District]]\n[[Category:Architects from Essex]]\n[[Category:Arts and Crafts architects]]\n\n\n{{England-bio-stub}}\n{{Architect-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Piecesofuk", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated date of birth; added ODNB reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_Thackeray_Turner"}
