{"title_page": "In the Forests of Serre", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = In the Forests of Serre\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = IntheForestsofSerre firsteditioncover.gif\n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[Patricia A. McKillip]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  = [[Kinuko Y. Craft]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Fantasy fiction|Fantasy]]\n| publisher     = [[Ace Books]]\n| release_date  = June 3, 2003\n| media_type    = Print \n| pages         = 304\n| isbn          = 0-441-01011-3\n| dewey         = 813/.54 21\n| congress= PS3563.C38 I5 2003\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n'''''In the Forests of Serre''''' is a 2003 [[fantasy]] novel by American writer [[Patricia A. McKillip]].  It was nominated for the 2004 [[Mythopoeic Award|Mythopoeic Fantasy Award for Adult Literature]].<ref>Mythopoeic Awards - Fantasy. {{cite web|url=http://www.mythsoc.org/awards/fantasy/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006201252/http://www.mythsoc.org/awards/fantasy/ |archivedate=2011-10-06 }}.  Retrieved 2009-10-22.</ref>\n\n==Summary==\nAfter the death of his wife and child, Prince Ronan falls into a depression so deep that even a fated encounter with the [[witch]] Brume leaves him unmoved.  He gives Brume his heart, certain that he no longer needs whatever is left of it, and then wanders through the forests of his country, escaping from an arranged marriage that his parents hope to force him into.  In the woods he becomes enchanted by a [[Firebird (Slavic folklore)|firebird]] and relentlessly pursues it, leaving behind his memories in his madness.\n\nAs her betrothed runs wildly through the wilderness, Princess Sidonie reluctantly leaves her home of Dacia to travel Serre. Her father and his [[Wizard (fantasy)|wizard]] Unciel realize that an alliance between Dacia and Serre will protect their country from war. To aid Sidonie and guard her from Serre's magic, Unciel arranges another wizard, Gyre, to escort her while Unciel, who is still weak from an earlier battle, and his scribe Euan Ash watch over the events from Dacia.  Gyre agrees, but has his own motivation for undertaking the journey.  Sidonie encounters the nearly delirious Ronan, though neither know who the other is; Gyre, aware of the prince's quest, takes advantage of the confused situation to steal Ronan's identity.\n\nWith the help of Unciel, who gathers his strength to settle the unfinished business he has with Gyre, Sidonie brings Ronan back from his wanderings and brings peace to both Serre and Dacia.\n\n==Nominations==\n*2004 [[Mythopoeic Awards|Mythopoeic Fantasy Award for Adult Literature]] Finalist\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Novels}}\n* [[Firebird (Slavic folklore)|Firebird]]\n* [[Baba Yaga]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Patricia A. McKillip}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:In The Forests Of Serre}}\n[[Category:2003 American novels]]\n[[Category:American fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Books with cover art by Kinuko Y. Craft]]\n[[Category:Novels by Patricia A. McKillip]]\n[[Category:Ace Books books]]\n\n\n{{2000s-fantasy-novel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = In the Forests of Serre\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = IntheForestsofSerre firsteditioncover.gif\n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[Patricia A. McKillip]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  = [[Kinuko Y. Craft]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Fantasy fiction|Fantasy]]\n| publisher     = [[Ace Books]]\n| release_date  = June 3, 2003\n| media_type    = Print \n| pages         = 304\n| isbn          = 0-441-01011-3\n| dewey         = 813/.54 21\n| congress= PS3563.C38 I5 2003\n| preceded_by   = [[Ombria in Shadow]]\n| followed_by   = [[Alphabet of Thorn]]\n}}\n'''''In the Forests of Serre''''' is a 2003 [[fantasy]] novel by American writer [[Patricia A. McKillip]].  It was nominated for the 2004 [[Mythopoeic Award|Mythopoeic Fantasy Award for Adult Literature]].<ref>Mythopoeic Awards - Fantasy. {{cite web|url=http://www.mythsoc.org/awards/fantasy/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006201252/http://www.mythsoc.org/awards/fantasy/ |archivedate=2011-10-06 }}.  Retrieved 2009-10-22.</ref>\n\n==Summary==\nAfter the death of his wife and child, Prince Ronan falls into a depression so deep that even a fated encounter with the [[witch]] Brume leaves him unmoved.  He gives Brume his heart, certain that he no longer needs whatever is left of it, and then wanders through the forests of his country, escaping from an arranged marriage that his parents hope to force him into.  In the woods he becomes enchanted by a [[Firebird (Slavic folklore)|firebird]] and relentlessly pursues it, leaving behind his memories in his madness.\n\nAs her betrothed runs wildly through the wilderness, Princess Sidonie reluctantly leaves her home of Dacia to travel Serre. Her father and his [[Wizard (fantasy)|wizard]] Unciel realize that an alliance between Dacia and Serre will protect their country from war. To aid Sidonie and guard her from Serre's magic, Unciel arranges another wizard, Gyre, to escort her while Unciel, who is still weak from an earlier battle, and his scribe Euan Ash watch over the events from Dacia.  Gyre agrees, but has his own motivation for undertaking the journey.  Sidonie encounters the nearly delirious Ronan, though neither know who the other is; Gyre, aware of the prince's quest, takes advantage of the confused situation to steal Ronan's identity.\n\nWith the help of Unciel, who gathers his strength to settle the unfinished business he has with Gyre, Sidonie brings Ronan back from his wanderings and brings peace to both Serre and Dacia.\n\n==Nominations==\n*2004 [[Mythopoeic Awards|Mythopoeic Fantasy Award for Adult Literature]] Finalist\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Novels}}\n* [[Firebird (Slavic folklore)|Firebird]]\n* [[Baba Yaga]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Patricia A. McKillip}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:In The Forests Of Serre}}\n[[Category:2003 American novels]]\n[[Category:American fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Books with cover art by Kinuko Y. Craft]]\n[[Category:Novels by Patricia A. McKillip]]\n[[Category:Ace Books books]]\n\n\n{{2000s-fantasy-novel-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BPK2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_the_Forests_of_Serre"}
